data.title: Tina Knowles reveals Beyonce was 'shy and got bullied' growing up as she praises her three 'special daughters', including Kelly Rowland: 'I'm getting emotional talking about it'
data.meta_description: Tina Knowlesgrew emotional reflecting on her proudest moments raising her three 'daughters' in their childhood. The momager, 70, opened up about Beyonce , Solange and Kelly Rowland.
data.text:
Tina Knowles grew emotional reflecting on her proudest moments raising her three daughters in their childhood.

The famous momager, 70, opened up about Beyonce, Solange and Kelly Rowland during a candid interview with Vogue, which she posted to her Instagram on Sunday.

Tina refers to Kelly as her third daughter, recently recalling to the Today show how the singer 'came to live' with the family at age 11, adding, 'That's my baby.'

'Each child is different! But all so special,' she wrote in the caption. 'I believe kids are born with their personalities. My three girls All handled things very differently. Learn their personalities and respect the individuality.'

She added: 'Never compare the negatives , always praise the positive differences and pay attention to the things that you can brag on about them. They love it and it encourages positive behavior.'

In the accompanying video, the business entrepreneur shared heartfelt examples of each daughter's moments that filled her with pride as they grew up.

'Beyonce was very shy and she got bullied a bit, but the day she stood up for someone, she didn't stand up for herself but she stood up for them... Im getting emotional just talking about it... and I couldn't have been more proud of her,' Tina said.

As for Solange, she recalled the Sandcastle Disco hitmaker starting a petition to sign at school.

'She was only in fifth grade and she was out getting petitions signed, so she's always been an activist,' Tina added with a huge smile.

Kelly, meanwhile, was 'always this kid that tried to protect everybody,' per TIna.

'I have a memory of her and her best friend Barbara and [Kelly] just being this little mediator and peace maker.'

The heartwarming clip comes after Tina came to the defense of Kelly in the wake of Kelly's verbal altercation with a security guard at Cannes Film Festival.

While attending the premiere of the French film Marcello Mio on Tuesday, May 21, the singer and actress got into a tense altercation with a security guard while walking up the red carpet towards the theater.

Just hours after the Dilemma star shared her side of the story on the incident, Knowles posted a message in support of Rowland.

'And just like that, she @kellyrowland graces another carpet with her amazing glorious beauty, class and grace!!!! Sipping Champagne and living her best life,' Knowles, 70, captioned a video showing Rowland back at another event at Cannes on Wednesday.

'This just goes to show that one silly monkey, don't stop no-show!!! on to bigger and and better things,' Rowland added, in a reference to the red carpet drama two days earlier.

A lip reader transcribed a video of the incident that seemingly began when the female security guard stepped on the train of Rowland's gown, to which she responded, 'Don't worry.'

The woman appeared to frantically respond to the Say My Name star, who even turned back to continue to make her point as she made her way up the rest of the steps.

It's not exactly clear what the worker said in response, but Rowland appeared to follow up and say, 'Don't talk to me like that. Don't talk to me like that. You're not my mother. I told you not to talk to me like that.'

A male security guard then came down to ask what was being said as the lady was using her hands to move Rowland along off the steps of the red carpet.

'You still don't talk to me like that!' she reiterated on last time before continuing her walk into the theater.

The Atlanta, Georgia native, 43, insisted she was just standing her ground.

'The woman knows what happened. I know what happened,' she said. 'And, I have a boundary. And I stand by those boundaries and that is it.'

She added, 'There were other women who attended that carpet, who did not quite look like me, and they didn't get scolded or pushed off or told to get off.'

It was claimed that the heated interaction came about because staff members were 'being aggressive', and eventually Rowland reached a boiling point with them.

'The people who are assigned to helping stars walk the red carpet were being aggressive and Kelly was trying to ignore it,' an insider told DailyMail.com.

In a show of class, the Talk A Good Game star took to her Instagram page after the premiere and red carpet drama to give thanks for the invite and to the glam team who helped make her red gown ensemble come together.

'Cannes Film Festival Red Carpet Thank you @kilianparis for having me!! '@messika for the [diamonds] and @anamikakhanna.in for the red dress,' Rowland wrote in an Instagram post the following day.
